
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `logname` esme karbar-e fa'al ra chap mikonad. Yani, esme shakhsi ke dar hale hazer be computer log-in karde ast ra neshon midehad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 Dastoor `logname` gozine khasi nadarad. Azash sade estefade mishe.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ logname

    🔹 Esme karbari ke log-in karde namayesh dade mishavad.

    $ whoami
    
    🔹 Dastoor `whoami` ham esme karbar-e fa'al ro neshon mide. Ba `logname` karayishoon ta ghariibeeh yeksane.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ logname
    ali

    🔹 Agar karbari ba esme "ali" be system log-in karde bashad, dastoor `logname` "ali" ra chap mikonad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `logname` command prints the name of the current user. It displays the username associated with the current login session.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 The `logname` command doesn't have specific options. It's used in its simplest form.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ logname

    🔹 Displays the username of the currently logged-in user.

    $ whoami

    🔹 The `whoami` command also displays the current username. Its functionality is similar to `logname`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ logname
    alice

    🔹 If a user with the username "alice" is logged into the system, the `logname` command will print "alice".

